<module>
    <h>có</h>
    <p><g>có</g>
        <en>who, what</en> is a question word (interrogative pronoun).</p>

    <section id="forms">
        <h>forms</h>
        <p>In post-1970s Neo-Gaelic orthography, the spelling has been standardised to <g>cò</g>,
            with a grave accent.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section>
            <h>complement</h>
            <p>The complement of <g>có</g> is introduced by the relative particle <a
                    href="?gd=a^relative"><g>a</g></a> (which is usually dropped in speech and often in writing).</p>
            <module id="coo_a_tha">
                <h>có a tha ... ?</h>
                <p>Used with the predicative verb, <g>có [a] <a href="?gd=bi">tha</a> ... ?</g>
                    <en>who is ... ?</en></p>
                <p>Examples where <g>có</g> stands for the subject – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Có tha a’ cluich air an làr? A’ chaileag.</gd>
                            <tr>Who is playing on the floor? The girl.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
                <module id="coo_a_bha">
                    <h>có a bha ... ?</h>
                    <p>The past tense variant of <g>có a tha ... ?</g> is <g>có a bha ... ?</g>
                        <en>who was ... ?</en>.</p>
                    <p>
                        <xl>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Có bha ag iasgach air an loch? Bha Calum.</gd>
                                <tr>Who was fishing on the lake? Calum was.</tr>
                                <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Có bha ag iasgach an diugh? Bha Alasdair.</gd>
                                <tr>Who was fishing today? Alexander was.</tr>
                                <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </p>
                </module>
            </module>
            <section id="deps-comp-other">
                <h>other verbs</h>
                <p>Examples where <g>có</g> stands for the subject – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Có chuir am bocsa air a’ bhòrd? Chuir Màiri.</gd>
                            <tr>Who put the box on the table? Mary did.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl></p>
            </section>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="uses-root">
            <h>root</h>
            <p><g>có</g> can be used as the root of a direct question.</p>
            <p>Examples where <g>có</g> stands for the subject – 
                <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Có tha a’ cluich air an làr? A’ chaileag.</gd>
                        <tr>Who is playing on the floor? The girl.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Có chuir am bocsa air a’ bhòrd? Chuir Màiri.</gd>
                        <tr>Who put the box on the table? Mary did.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>





